<DOC><DOCNO> AP880504-0350 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 1904EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u f BC-AutoSales 1stLd-Writethru   05-04 0279</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Auto Sales, 1st Ld - Writethru,0283</SECOND><HEAD>Auto Companies Report April Monthly Sales Slide</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: SUBs grafs 6th graf pvs, Among import... to include figuresfor domestically-made cars. Picks up 7th graf, Honda import...</NOTE><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Sales of domestically made cars fell 6.7 percentin late April, with Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. posting salesgains and General Motors Corp. reporting a decline, the companiesreported Wednesday.   GM said its car sales for the April 21-30 period trailed 19.7percent behind unusually strong sales in the same period last year.   Chrysler posted a 10.3 percent gain for the period and Ford'scar sales were up 8.7 percent.   Domestic truck sales showed a 6.5 percent increase, but combinedcar and truck sales were still down 2.6 percent from the year-agolate April period.   For the month, GM's car sales were down 14.2 percent to a314,671 total, Ford's car sales were down 1.4 percent to 186,175and Chrysler up 8.8 percent to 95,170.   Among import carmakers, Toyota's April sales of domesticallymade cars rose by 4.5 percent to 4,115, while sales of its importedcars rose 0.6 percent from the previous April to 43,605. Volkswagendomestic auto sales fell 11 percent to 4,625 while its import salesfell 25 percent to 11,922.   Honda import sales dropped 3.6 percent to 19,702, but sales ofdomestically made Hondas were up 7.5 percent to 17,512.   David Healy, analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in NewYork, said a GM surge due to sales incentives last April skewed thefigures. ``They were 55 percent of the market, so the comparisonwill be kind of distorted. GM will look poor,'' he said.</TEXT></DOC>